From 2a8cf0b4d0c636fb750f604d99a8906636c7d8b8 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alexandre Cordeiro <nenisdeno@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 21 May 2026 19:02:25 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] Refine _schedule_waiting memory-pressure admission to
 per-request rejection
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Previously, two pre-pop guards in _schedule_waiting broke the entire
loop when self._admission_paused was set OR when the generation
memory guard tripped:

    if self._admission_paused and self.running: break
    if memory_over_limit: break

Under sustained backpressure with a multi-request queue, this was
head-of-line-blocking — none of the queued waiters could progress
until pressure cleared, even when individual requests' sizes would
have fit comfortably under the current budget.

Refined per-request behaviour: pop the head first, then ask the
existing _preflight_memory_check whether THIS specific request can
fit. On rejection finalize it with finish_reason='error' (same
RequestOutput shape as the downstream preflight rejection a hundred
lines later in the same loop) and ``continue`` so the loop keeps
trying subsequent waiters. Requests whose preflight math accepts
them still get admitted under pressure.

First-request semantics preserved: both guards only fire when
``self.running`` is non-empty, matching the prior conservative
"first request always passes so admission can recover" behaviour.

Why this is safe
================

_preflight_memory_check is already the canonical per-request
memory gate; it's called downstream in the same loop at the
"normal" admission rejection path. The refinement just calls it
earlier when a global pressure signal is set, surfaces the same
finish_reason='error' RequestOutput, and avoids the whole-loop
break. No new memory-math code; no new admission policy; just
flow-control.

Composition
===========

* Independent of C.1 (Metal-error recovery on the decode + prefill
  catches) and C.2 (per-model concurrency caps). The change is
  purely flow-control in _schedule_waiting.
* Pairs naturally with the dispatch-side preflight guard the
  ModelHost backend already uses — clients hitting transient
  pressure get an immediate finish_reason='error' they can retry
  against instead of hanging behind another request.

Tests
=====

tests/test_admission_pause_refinement.py covers:
- Mixed-size queue under pressure: small request admitted, large
  rejected.
- Multi-request queue with all-too-large requests: every waiter
  gets a rejected_output (loop iterates over all instead of
  breaking after the first).
